@10190 = ~Jack Of All Trades~
@10191 = ~Both the creator and previous owners of this peculiar cloak, much like the garment itself, have been largely lost to history. Whether ‘Jack’ was once its wearer or simply a namesake is unclear, but whoever they were, the cloak has long outlasted them.

The earliest surviving record of the cloak appears in a merchant ledger from Berdusk, where it was listed in its inventory before disappearing entirely. In the years since, it has surfaced in tales of a duelist in Riatavin who swore it gave him the reflexes of a cat, and a mage living in the Sunset Mountains who claimed it helped her survive the harsh environments.

The cloak adjusts itself from owner to owner—the seams shift, colors blur, and the weight in the hem seems to come and go. It attunes itself to the wearer and their needs, and sits snugly as though it were designed for them alone. It offers just enough to make them feel exceptional—but never quite enough to make it feel like theirs.

Most who wear it accomplish great things, though few keep it for long.

Equipped abilities:
The benefits of this item depend on the class(es) of the wearer. The cloak will adapt to the wearer's class and the overall weight of their affinity, granting them the following abilities:
– Martial proficiencies: +1 to Constitution, +5% physical and magic damage resistance. Applies to all single and multi-classed fighters, paladins, monks, rangers, and bards
– Full priestly proficiencies: +2 to casting speed, +2 saves vs. Death. Applies to all single and multi-classed clerics
– Partial priestly proficiencies: This only applies to Paladins and Blackguards. Bonuses are halved
– Full rogue proficiencies: +1 to THAC0, +1 to Dexterity, +5% to thieving skills. Applies to all single and multi-classed thieves, and bards
– Partial rogue proficiencies: This applies to Rangers and Monks. The THAC0 bonus is not granted.
– Full druidic proficiencies: 1/HP per round regeneration, +10% resistance to elements. Applies to all single and multi-classed druids, and shamans
– Partial druidic proficiencies: This only applies to Rangers. The regeneration bonus is three times slower and the elemental resistances are halved
– Prepared arcane proficiency: +10% elemental and magic resistance, +2 Saves vs. Spell. Applies to all single and multi-classed mages, as well as bards
– Spontaneous casting proficiency: One additional 4th and 5th level spell slot. Applies to all sorcerers and shamans


Weight: 3~

@10200 = ~Festering Maw +3~
@10201 = ~Forged by the lizardfolk shamans of the Mere of Dead Men, this grotesque weapon has passed from one sovereign of the Slavering Maw clan to the next, its blade anointed in the blood of those too weak to rule. The halberd’s jagged blade is coated in old bloodstains and dark patina that glows brightly under the lightless sky of the dark moon. Clan lore holds that the blade remembers every life taken, and grows sharper for each.

How this weapon that even most lizardfolk dread to touch left the Mere is unknown, though its presence in the realms is rarely subtle. The Festering Maw announces itself in the bodies it leaves behind, rotting from wounds that should not fester. Healers weep in the face of this sickness that resists their prayers, while wiser tongues suggest the weapon was never meant for battle alone, but as the shadow that a savage ruler can cast.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Each successful hit forces the target to save vs. Death at -2 or become diseased. Afflicted targets take 1 poison damage per round for 1 turn and are slowed for 2 rounds.

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d10+3, +1d4 poison damage
Damage type: Piercing or slashing, whichever is better
Speed Factor: 6
Proficiency Type: Halberd
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 13 Strength

Weight: 11~


@10210 = ~Binky~
@10211 = ~This is the skeleton of a racing lizard that Jan received by trading for Lissa's prize turnip.

